      modeling complex physical phenomena in domains ranging from
      climate to aerodynamics. Fluid flows are well described by
      Navier-Stokes equations, but solving these equations at all scales
      remains extremely complex in many situations. The increased
      availability of large amounts of high fidelity data and the recent
      development of powerful machine learning methods has motivated a
      surge of recent work for using machine learning in the context of
      computational fluid dynamics (CFD). The objective of the thesis is
      to develop the interplay between Deep Learning (DL) and CFD in
      order to improve turbulence modeling and to challenge state of the
      art ML techniques.<br>
